result.execSummary:
The defendant Andre L Singley Sr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case call for court to formally enter judgment of conviction on count 1 on 8-2-2017. No appearances made.

Defendant Andre L Singley in court with attorney Vincent Paul Guimont.  Defendant Andre L Singley in custody.  Gilbert Fielding Urfer appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.   

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  2 YEARS with 0 days credit CONSECUTIVE to case 12CF2824 and CONCURRENT to 17Cf2008; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR.

Court finds defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and/or the WI Substance Abuse program.  

Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 2 YEARS probation.

  Conditions of Probation/ Extended Supervision if revoked:
- Fine set at zero.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- No use of alcohol or controlled substances without a valid prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Random urine screens.
- No contact with drug users.
- Obtain/maintain employment of no less than 35 hours.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.

Defendant Andre L Singley in court with attorney Vincent Paul Guimont.  Defendant Andre L Singley in custody.  Gilbert Fielding Urfer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defendant and defense in agreement.

AS TO COUNT 1: Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information. 

AS TO COUNT 2:   Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered count 2 dismissed and read-in to case for the purposes of sentencing.

Parties prepared to proceed with sentencing.  Statements by the State. Due to the late hour court adjourns case until 1:30 pm to continue.
